1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 {This is one of the most
classical Caro-Kann positions. After 5.Be2, Black has many opportunities. I
think that the system with 3.e5 and 5 Be2 is White's most dangerous weapon.
The e5-pawn gives White a long-term space advantage and makes it difficult for
Black to develop his kingside pieces. Black has a huge choice here. There are
many possible setups and transpositions. Some of the lines are not concrete
and you just need to know the typical plans and ideas. On the other hand,
there are lines in which Black is trying to achieve immediate equality. In
such lines, the play is getting pretty forced and concrete knowledge is
required. I tried to make the repertoire as practical as possible. That is the
reason why I provide you with a number of rare and almost unexplored lines and
concepts. Even though getting an objective advantage is not always possible,
my suggestions will allow you to create practical problems for your opponent.
In this chapter, we are going to deal with some of Black's rare options.} Bb4+
$5 {Sometimes this move is used by good players. Black wants to relocate the
bishop to c7 and make space for the knights. Being on c7, the bishop will be
able to support Black's typical ...f7-f6 ideas.} (5... Qb6 $6 {This move is
dubious. Black is behind in the development and the queen alone will not be
able to create serious threats.} 6. O-O Nd7 ({Playing in the centre with} 6...
c5 $2 {is of course very dangerous since Black is underdeveloped.} 7. c4 dxc4 (
{After} 7... Ne7 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc8 10. Nd4 Bxb1 11. Rxb1 a6 12. Rc1 $16 {
[%cal Gc1c8] White's initiative is almost decisive.}) 8. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] A
typical idea in this structure. The c4-square is perfect for the knight. Later
on, if the dark-squared bishops are being exchanged, the knight will occupy
the d6-square.} Nc6 9. Nxc4 Qc7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Rc1 Kb8 {This position was
seen in the game 1-0 (55) Ponkratov,P (2630)-Daneshvar,B (2283) Tehran IRI
2019. At this point, my suggestion would be} 12. Qa4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Nd6
Nxe2+ 15. Kh1 $18 {and White is winning.}) 7. c4 $5 {White immediately breaks
in the centre and seizes the initiative.} dxc4 ({The passive} 7... Ne7 {allows}
8. c5 Qc7 9. Nc3 {Very often, in this structure, White closes the queenside
and starts advancing his kingside pawns. For example, White can already
consider playing Nh4 followed by f2-f4, g2-g4, and possibly f4-f5.} b6 10. cxb6
axb6 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. Be3 Nf5 {Black frees the e7-square for the bishop but
White gets extra tempos for this kingside attack.} 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. g4 Bg6 15.
f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] White is already threatening to play g4-f5, therefore radical
measures are required.} f5 16. Bd3 {It turns out that Black cannot hold the
blockade on f5.} Bb4 17. gxf5 Bxf5 18. Bxf5 exf5 19. Qc2 {[%csl Rc7][%cal
Gc2f5,Gc3d5,Gc2c7]} Bxc3 20. bxc3 O-O 21. c4 $16 {White is better.}) {Again,
we can see the same recurring motif. White wants to take the c4-pawn with a
knight.} 8. Nbd2 Qc7 ({The move} 8... Bd3 {does not solve Black's problems. A
possible line would be} 9. Bxd3 cxd3 10. a4 a5 11. Ne4 Bb4 12. Bd2 {In this
structure, it is very difficult for Black to prevent the exchange of the
dark-squared bishops. After such an exchange, the white knight will land on d6.
} Be7 13. Qb1 h5 14. Qxd3 Nh6 15. Bg5 $16 {White is better. He has more space
and there is no safe place for Black's king.}) 9. Nh4 $5 {Exchanging Black's
light-squared bishop is an important part of White's strategy in this
structure.} Bd3 10. Nxc4 Bxc4 11. Bxc4 Ne7 12. Bd2 Nb6 13. Bd3 g6 14. Nf3 Bg7
15. a4 O-O 16. a5 Nbd5 17. h4 $14 {White has more space and he will gradually
build a kingside attack.}) (5... Be7 $5 {[%cal Gf5g6,Gg8h6,Gh6f5] Black wants
to execute the following regrouping: ...Nh6 followed by ...Bg6 and ...Nf5. In
practical games, this option is rare.} 6. O-O Nh6 (6... h5 {looks too
ambitious. Black begins pushing the pawns of the kingside, which only weakens
the king. The following example line is a good illustration of Black's
problems.} 7. Nbd2 g5 8. Ne1 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ge2d3,Ge1d3] White clears the way in
front of the f-pawn and prepares Bd3.} g4 9. Nb3 Nd7 10. Bd3 Nh6 11. Bxh6 Bxd3
12. Nxd3 Rxh6 13. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] Making use of the weakened kingside.} a5 14.
a4 b6 15. f5 Bg5 16. fxe6 fxe6 17. Qe2 $14 {White has more space and better
coordination. Additionally, the black king will be permanently weak.}) 7. a4 $5
{A typical idea in this structure. On the queenside, White tries to capture as
much space as possible. Sometimes, White can even close the queenside and
start playing on the other wing.} O-O 8. a5 Bg6 9. Nbd2 Nd7 10. Nb3 Nf5 11. g4
{Another very important move which illustrates the drawback of Black's
strategy. It turns out that the f5-knight is unstable.} Nh4 ({Passive is} 11...
Nh6 {when White should follow with} 12. Ne1 f6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. f4 {
restricting black minor pieces to the maximum.} Be7 15. Bd3 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Bd6
17. h3 Nf7 18. Qe2 Qe7 19. Be3 $14 {White is better. He has more space and can
start playing against Black's weaknesses.}) 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 f6 14. Be3 $14
{White has a solid advantage.}) ({The manoeuvre...Nh6-f5 can be realized also
without the prior ...Be7.} 5... Bg6 6. O-O Nh6 (6... Ne7 $5 {is dealt within
Chapter 3}) (6... Nd7 $5 {is covered in Chapter 6}) 7. Nbd2 {White carries out
the usual plan in this position. He transfers the knight to b3 in order to
restrict Black's queenside play. At a convenient moment White shall start
pushing his kingside pawns.} Nf5 8. Nb3 Nd7 9. a4 Be7 10. g4 {As we have
already witnessed, g2-g4 is a recurring theme in this pawn structure. White
gains space on the kingside and drives the f5-knight away.} Nh4 ({As usual,
passive is} 10... Nh6 11. Ne1 O-O 12. f4 Be4 13. Nd3 Rc8 14. Nf2 Bg6 15. c3 $16
{when White has an advantage.}) 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5]} f5 13. Bd3
O-O 14. g5 {[%csl Rh4] Black should take measures against the idea Qf3-h3.} h6
15. gxh6 gxh6 16. Qf3 Kh7 17. Kh1 Qe7 18. Be3 Rg8 19. a5 $14 {White controls
both wings.}) (5... h6 6. O-O g5 {This strategy is very risky when all the
pieces (except the f5-bishop) remain on their initial positions.} (6... Ne7 $5
{This position is mentioned in Chapter 3}) (6... Nd7 $5 {is covered in Chapter
6)}) 7. c4 $5 {White immediately breaks in the centre. According to the
classical rules of chess, we respond to an attack on the wing with a
breakthrough in the centre.} dxc4 8. Bxc4 {Had the Black pawn been on g7,
instead of g5, we would have had a normal structure with a slight advantage
for White. In this line of thoughts, one can say that Black's best move would
be g5-g7 (if it was allowed)!} Nd7 9. Nc3 Ne7 10. Qe2 Nb6 11. Bb3 Ned5 12. Ne4
Qd7 13. Bd2 Be7 14. Nc5 Qc7 15. Rfc1 $14 {White has an advantage. He can
already start thinking of provoking queenside weaknesses by means of the
thematic a2-a4-a5-a6.}) (5... a6 {Strangely enough, this dubious move has been
tried by Karpov, Motylev, and Epishin. It looks like Black is losing an
important tempo.} 6. O-O Nd7 7. Nbd2 Bg6 ({The move} 7... Ne7 {allows the
typical} 8. Nh4 {when White takes the bishop pair.} c5 9. c3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Rc8
11. Nxf5 Nxf5 12. Nf3 {The position is already stable. White has a pair of
bishops, more space and he can start grabbing space on the kingside. At the
same time, Black's counterplay is problematic.} Be7 13. g4 Nh4 14. Nxh4 Bxh4
15. Be3 O-O 16. f4 $14 {White is better.}) (7... c5 {This move does not go
well with ...Nd7. In order to put pressure on the centre, Black should play ...
Ne7-c6. This manoeuvre, however, is rather time-consuming. White seizes the
opportunity to strike in the centre.} 8. c4 {The tension in the centre is in
White's favour since his pieces are better developed.} Ne7 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Nb3
Nd7 (10... Nxb3 11. Qxb3 Qc8 12. Bg5 $14) 11. Nbd4 Be4 12. Ng5 $5 {White
begins an attack on the king.} Nxe5 13. Bf4 N7g6 14. Be3 {White has more than
enough compensation for the pawn. Below, I provide some example lines which
confirm this evaluation.} h6 ({The complications arising after} 14... Be7 15.
Ngxe6 fxe6 16. Nxe6 Qd7 17. cxd5 Rc8 18. Bg4 Qxd5 19. Nxg7+ Kf8 20. Bxc8 Kxg7
21. Bh3 Rf8 22. Qxd5 Bxd5 23. Rfd1 Bc6 24. Be6 $14 {turn out to be in White's
favor.}) 15. Nxe4 (15. Ngxe6 $5 fxe6 16. Nxe6 Qd7 17. cxd5 $13) 15... dxe4 16.
Qc2 Nd3 17. Bxd3 exd3 18. Qxd3 Be7 19. Qe4 Qd7 20. f4 O-O 21. f5 exf5 22. Nxf5
$14 {The powerful knight on f5 gives White an advantage.}) 8. c4 {White
carries out a standard plan. In the future, Black will feel the loss of an
important tempo.} Ne7 9. Nh4 Nf5 10. Nxf5 Bxf5 11. Qb3 Qb6 12. Qe3 $5 {White
saves the queens and begins a pawn assault on both wing.} Be7 13. c5 Qc7 14. a4
O-O 15. b4 f6 16. f4 fxe5 17. fxe5 a5 18. b5 b6 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Ba3 Bxa3 21.
Qxa3 cxb5 22. axb5 $14 {White is better.}) 6. Nbd2 {This is the most solid
continuation. White develops the knight without losing time on c2-c3. In any
case, Black is planning to transfer his bishop to c7.} Nd7 ({The move} 6... Ne7
{allows White to grab the bishop pair.} 7. c3 Ba5 8. Nh4 $1 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 10.
Nxf5 Nxf5 11. Bd3 {The position is stable and White can already focus on the
kingside. Black's only hope for counterplay is} f6 {Nevertheless, after} 12.
Bxf5 exf5 13. e6 Nb8 14. Nb3 Bc7 15. Re1 Re8 16. Nc5 $14 {White has the
advantage since the e6-pawn is very strong.}) 7. O-O Ba5 {Acting according to
plan! Black makes the most useful move in the position.} ({As usual,} 7... Ne7
$6 {grants White the bishop pair.} 8. c3 Ba5 9. Nh4 O-O 10. Nxf5 Nxf5 11. Bd3
$16 {with an advantage.}) 8. a4 $5 {We already know this typical idea. White
is just planning to grab space on the queenside.} h6 {[%cal Gg8e7]
Prophylactic move. Black has prepared the retreat of the bishop to h7 and now
they are ready for the development of the knight on e7.} ({Another option is} 
8... Bc7 9. Nb3 {[%cal Ga4a5]} a5 {Black fixes the structure on the queenside
and prevents White from further gaining space.} 10. Bg5 {This important tempo
gives White the initiative.} Ne7 (10... f6 11. Bh4 Ne7 12. exf6 gxf6 {The
position of the black king is weakened. This gives White a good chance of an
attack.} (12... Nxf6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Nc5 Qc8 15. Re1 $14 {With pressure on the
weak e6-pawn.}) 13. Bg3 O-O 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. Nh4 e5 16. Nxf5 Nxf5 17. c4 $1
dxc4 18. Bxc4+ Kh8 19. Be6 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 exd4 21. Qxd4 $14 {Black's position
is unpleasant due to the numerous pawn weaknesses.}) 11. Nh4 Be4 12. f3 Bg6 13.
f4 Be4 (13... h6 14. Nxg6 fxg6 15. Bh4 $16) 14. f5 {Black is in a dangerous
position.} exf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Rxf5 h6 17. Bh5 hxg5 (17... g6 18. Bh4 gxf5
19. e6 O-O 20. Qe2 Nb6 21. exf7+ Rxf7 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Re1 Qd6 24. Qxe7+ Kg8
25. Nc5 Qxe7 26. Rxe7 $16) 18. Bxf7+ Kf8 19. Rf2 Ng8 20. Bxd5+ Ngf6 21. Bc4
Bxe5 22. dxe5 Nxe5 23. Qe2 $16) (8... f6 {Black's pieces are not ready for
active play. Therefore, this breakthrough is premature.} 9. Nb3 Bc7 10. Re1
fxe5 11. dxe5 Ne7 12. Nbd4 c5 13. Nxf5 Nxf5 14. Bg5 Qc8 15. c4 d4 16. Bd3 O-O
17. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge2e4] White's advantage is obvious. He can already
start thinking of a kingside attack. A good idea would be the manoeuvre Qe2-e4.}
) 9. Nb3 Bc7 ({Worse is} 9... Ne7 {when White takes advantage of the bishop
pair. Additionally, White's space advantage is very big.} 10. Nxa5 Qxa5 11. c3
{[%cal Gb2b4,Ga4a5] planning to expand on the queenside by means of b2-b4 and
a4-a5.} ({Another interesting idea is} 11. b3 $5 {trying to make use of the
diagonal a3-f8. You shall take a look at the lines below.} O-O 12. Ba3 Rfe8 13.
Rc1 Rac8 14. Re1 Bg4 15. c4 dxc4 16. bxc4 Nb6 17. Bd6 Nf5 (17... Nxa4 18. Qb3
Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nf5 20. Red1 b5 21. g4 Nh4 22. Be4 Qd8 23. f4 $44) 18. c5 Nd5 19.
h3 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 $14) 11... O-O 12. b4 Qc7 13. a5 b6 14. Be3 c5 15. Qa4 c4 16.
Nh4 {Once the queenside is closed, White can already start expanding on the
kingside.} Be4 17. Qd1 Rfb8 18. f3 Bh7 19. f4 $14 {White will gradually
prepare the advance f4-f5. At the same time, Black runs out of counterplay.})
10. a5 $1 Ne7 11. Nh4 $5 {A recurring idea. After taking space on the
queenside, White starts playing on the kingside.} Be4 12. f3 Bh7 13. f4 O-O 14.
Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5] White threatens to follow with f4-f5. His
advantage is obvious.} *

