1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 {Not the most principled
option. Nevertheless, this move is very popular because of its flexibility.}
6. O-O Bg6 {This move got popular recently. Black frees the f5-square for the
knight. The problem is that the knight does not manage to find stability on
that square.} (6... Nc8 $6 {This is a very passive move which is often played
by GM Vladimir Burmakin. Black just wants to complete the development with ...
Be7 followed by ...0-0. The main goal of such an approach is to avoid studying
theory.} 7. b3 $5 {White is planning to gain space on the queenside by means
of c2-c4.} Be7 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 Nd7 10. Bd3 {An important decision. Exchanging
the light-squared bishops would help White to generate a kingside activity.}
Bxd3 ({Avoiding the exchange with} 10... Bg4 {does not help either. White can
follow with} 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Kg2 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 a6 15. a4 {Black has
no counterplay in this position. White can think of playing on both wings.} {
The move} f6 {should be answered with} 16. exf6 Rxf6 17. Ne2 Nd6 18. Ng3 $14 {
with an obvious advantage.}) 11. Qxd3 f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bf4 $16
{Wagner-Burmakin 2018 1-0, Zurich. Black does not have a compensation for the
lack of space and the weakness of e6.}) (6... Ng6 {Recently, this continuation
got popular. Black wants to quickly develop his pieces and challenge the
centre by means of ...f7-f6.} 7. Be3 Nd7 ({Premature is} 7... f6 {since Black
is not developed enough.} 8. c4 {White is immediately attacking the centre.}
Nd7 9. Nc3 $5 {A promising pawn sacrifice.} ({After} 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Qb3 Qc7
11. h3 Bd6 12. Nbd2 O-O $132 {Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 9... fxe5 10.
dxe5 Ndxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bd4 Bd6 14. Bh5+ Kf8 15. Re1 Ng6 16.
g3 Qd7 17. Qf3 Qf7 18. Re3 $44 {White enjoys a very strong initiative for the
sacrificed pawn.}) 8. Ne1 $5 {The main idea is to strengthen the centre with
f2-f4. Meanwhile, White creates the threat of g2-g4 with the idea to capture
the bishop.} h5 9. c3 ({The careless} 9. Nd2 $6 {allows} Ndxe5 $1 10. dxe5 d4
11. Nc4 dxe3 12. fxe3 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bc5 $11) 9... c5 ({Another direction is} 
9... h4 {when White should go for} 10. Bd3 {As we have already pointed out,
the exchange of the light-squared bishops gives White a free-hand on the
kingside.} Ne7 11. Nd2 Bxd3 12. Nxd3 Nf5 13. Qg4 (13. Nf3 Be7 $132 {Sychev,
K-Sargsyan ,A 2019 0.5-0.5 Yerevan}) 13... Be7 14. Nf3 Rc8 15. h3 $14 {White
is better due to his space advantage and the attacking prospects on the
kingside. Black doesn't have a clear way to create counterplay.}) ({White is
ready to meet} 9... f6 {with} 10. f4 {when the game could continue} Qb6 11. Qd2
Be7 12. a4 a5 13. Na3 O-O-O 14. Nd3 $14 {White is better. He is ready to open
the queenside by means of b2-b4.}) 10. Nd2 a6 ({Pointless is} 10... h4 {
since Black weakens the g4-square, thus making the ideas with Bg4 possible.}
11. a4 $1 {Before exchanging the bishops via g4, White grabs space on the
queenside.} a6 12. a5 Be7 13. Bg4 Bxg4 14. Qxg4 cxd4 15. cxd4 O-O 16. Nd3 $16 {
White has a huge advantage in this position. He is ready to follow with
f2-f4-f5.}) 11. a3 c4 12. a4 h4 13. a5 $1 {As the reader might have already
noticed, fixing the queenside pawns is a typical idea for White.} Qc7 14. f4
$14 {White got an advantage in the game Durarbeyli, V-Xiong, Jeffery 2019 1-0
Chicago open} ({Even more precise, however is} 14. b3 $1 cxb3 15. Qxb3 Be7 16.
c4 dxc4 17. Nxc4 $16 {with a tremendous advantage.})) 7. c3 $5 {White
strengthens the centre and prepares the development of his pieces.} Nf5 ({
the move} 7... Nd7 {transposes to 8...Nd7.}) 8. Nbd2 h5 {Black secures the
knight against any g2-g4 ideas but weakens the kingside.} ({The principled} 
8... c5 {is very well met by} 9. Nb3 $1 {You should remember this positional
idea. White provokes Black to close the centre with ...c5-c4. In such a case,
he will have a free hand on the kingside.} ({After} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c4 dxc4
11. Nxc4 O-O 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. Rc1 $11 {White doesn't have an advantage.}) 9...
c4 ({The attempt to keep the tension with} 9... Nd7 {is well met by} 10. dxc5 {
when Black is forced to give the bishop pair} Bxc5 ({The careless} 10... Nxc5
$2 {runs into} 11. Nxc5 Bxc5 12. Qa4+ $16 {when Black loses the right to
castle.}) 11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. Nd4 O-O 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Bd4 $14 {
White enjoys a bishop pair, space advantage and a clear plan. He just wants to
expand on the kingside by means of g2-g4 followed by f2-f4-f5.1/2 (30)
Demchenko,A (2632)-Antonio,R (2481) Subic Bay 2016}) 10. Nbd2 Nc6 11. g4 $1 {
A thematic idea in such positions. Now, White just needs to remove the
f3-knight and follow with f2-f4.} Nh4 ({Another option is} 11... Nfe7 {when
the game might continue} 12. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} h5 13. gxh5 Bh7 14. f4
Nf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Rf2 g6 17. hxg6 Bxg6 18. Nf3 Be7 19. Ng5 $14 {White has
a healthy pawn up.}) 12. Nxh4 Qxh4 13. f4 f6 ({After} 13... h5 14. g5 Be7 15.
Rf2 $14 {the black queen is in a dangerous position.}) 14. f5 Bf7 15. Kh1 fxe5
16. Nf3 Qd8 17. dxe5 $16 {Giri,A-Svetushkin,D 2013 1-0 Linares} (17. Ng5 $5 $16
)) (8... Nd7 9. a4 $5 {A thematic idea in this structure. Before proceeding
with his kingside expansion, White gains space on the queenside.} a5 {Black
prevents White from gaining even more space but weakens the queenside. Now,
the typical c6-c5 would be positionally unjustified because of the weakness of
the b5-square.} ({Another option would be} 9... Be7 10. a5 O-O 11. b4 f6 12.
Nb3 {White is ready to meet 12...fxe5 with 13.dxe5 after which the b3-knight
can be placed on d4.} Qc7 13. Bf4 fxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Nxd6
17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 $14 {The weak pawn on e6 gives White a small advantage.})
10. Nb3 h5 {As usual, Black prevents the idea g2-g4 but weakens the kingside.}
({After} 10... Be7 {White goes for the immediate} 11. g4 $1 Nh4 ({The
structure arising after} 11... Nh6 12. Ne1 f6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. f4 {is very
unpleasant for Black. The weak e6-pawn and the lack of space make Black's
counterplay rather difficult.} Be7 15. Bf3 Nf7 16. Nd3 O-O 17. Re1 $14 {
White's advantage is obvious.}) 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 f5 14. Bd3 Be7 15. Be3 O-O
16. g5 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 11. g3 $5 {[%csl Gg5][%cal
Gh2h4,Gc1g5] An important idea in such positions. Anticipating Black's ...Be7,
White makes use of the weak g5-square by preparing the exchange of the dark-squared bishops.} Be7 12. h4 Qb6 13. Bg5 Bxg5 14. Nxg5 $14 {White made a
profitable exchange of the bishops and captured the important g5-square. Later
on, he can transfer his b3-knight to f4. It is important to point out that the
black king has no safe haven in this position. If Black decides to castle
long, White can make use of the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 by
opening up the queenside with b2-b4.}) 9. a4 Nd7 10. a5 a6 11. b4 {The
queenside is closed. The active actions on the kingside can start.} h4 12. Ne1
f6 13. Nd3 Qc7 14. Nf3 h3 15. g3 Bf7 16. Nc5 $16 {with a huge advantage.
Bosiocic, M-Nisipeanu, LD 2019 0.5-0.5 Zagreb} ({Another way to keep the
e5-square under control would have been} 16. Re1 $5 O-O-O 17. Bf1 $16) *

