1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 {Not the most principled
option. Nevertheless, this move is very popular because of its flexibility.}
6. O-O c5 {Black is planning to follow with ...Nec6 and ...Nd7, thus achieving
a perfect placement for his knights. The drawback is that this idea takes a
lot of time. Of course, we shall take a look at the alternatives to 6...c5.} 7.
c4 {An important breakthrough! White starts active actions in the centre,
making use of his better development.} ({After} 7. c3 {Black carries out his
plan and solves all the problems.} Nec6 8. Be3 Nd7 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. dxc5 Bxc5
11. Nd4 Ncxe5 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Bb5+ Kf8 $11) 7... Nbc6 {This is
the most natural continuation.} ({An alternative is} 7... dxc4 {when I would
suggest} 8. dxc5 $5 {which creates big practical problems for Black.} Nd5 (8...
Nbc6 9. Bxc4 {transposes to 7...Nbc6.}) 9. Bxc4 Bxc5 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. Bxd5 exd5
12. Nc3 h6 13. Bh4 (13. Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Nc6 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Nxd5 Rd8 17.
Nc3 Bg4 $11) 13... Be6 {White looks better. But the computer protects any
position with precise moves. Below, I provide a sample line which illustrates
the character of the position.} 14. Qd3 ({The idea} 14. Na4 $5 {deserves
attention as well.} Bb6 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Nd4 (16. Qd2 O-O 17. b3 Nc6 18. Qf4
d4 $15) (16. Bg3 Nc6 17. Nh4 O-O 18. f4 Ne7 $11) 16... O-O 17. f4 Nc6 18. Bf2
Nxd4 19. Bxd4 $11 {White's position is slightly more pleasant but Black should
be able to equalize.}) 14... Nc6 15. Rfd1 g5 16. Bg3 O-O-O 17. Rac1 Kb8 18. Qb5
(18. Nb5 Bb6 19. Nd6 $132) 18... Be7 19. Nxd5 h5 20. Ne3 Qc7 21. h4 gxh4 22.
Nxh4 a6 23. Qa4 Qb6 24. Nc4 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Qc5 26. Ne3 $132 {with mutual
chances.}) 8. dxc5 $5 {Temporarily winning a pawn and proceeding with the
central activity.} (8. Na3 $5 {Also an interesting option.}) 8... d4 {An
interesting move which is also the most popular continuation in this position.
Black closes the centre and moves the passed pawn forward.} (8... dxc4 $5 {
also deserves attention.} 9. Bxc4 $5 {Simple and strong. White is winning back
the pawn.} Ng6 10. Be3 {Keeping the more important c5-pawn. In the future,
White will make use of his queenside majority.} Be7 11. Qb3 {This is a
novelty which poses practical problems for Black.} ({An alternative is} 11. Nc3
$5 {when after} O-O 12. Be2 Qb8 13. Nd2 Rd8 14. f4 Nb4 15. Rc1 b6 16. c6 Nxc6
17. Bf3 {White was slightly better in the game 1-0 (42) Harikrishna, P (2729)
-Mamedyarov,S (2817) Kolkata 2018}) 11... O-O 12. Be2 (12. Qxb7 Na5 13. Qa6
Nxc4 14. Qxc4 Bd3 $15) 12... Qb8 13. Nbd2 Ngxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rac1 Ng4 16.
Bxg4 Bxg4 17. f3 Bf5 18. Nc4 Rd8 19. Rfd1 Qc7 20. Nd6 $14 {The powerful knight
on d6 gives White an advantage.}) 9. Bd3 $5 {The most reliable continuation.
Exchanging the strong bishop and at the same time blocking the passed pawn.}
Bxd3 (9... Bg4 $6 {gives White the bishop pair.} 10. Nbd2 Ng6 (10... Nxe5 $6
11. Be4 $1 N7c6 12. b4 Be7 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 $16) 11. h3
Ngxe5 (11... Bxf3 12. Nxf3 Bxc5 13. Re1 Qc7 14. a3 a5 15. Qe2 O-O 16. h4 $16)
12. Be4 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Bxc5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. b4 $1 Be7 16. Bf4 Ng6 17. Bg3 Qd7
18. Qf3 O-O 19. c5 $14 {White's advantage is obvious.}) 10. Qxd3 Ng6 11. Qe4 $5
{Strengthening the e5-pawn and at the same time, the queen will be relocated
to the kingside and will create threats to the king.} (11. Nbd2 $5) 11... Bxc5
12. Nbd2 {The knight goes to b3, attacking the c5-bishop and the d4-pawn.} Qb6
{This seems to be the most precise move.} (12... O-O $5 {transposes to the
main line after} 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. h4 $36) (12... Qc7 {is rather passive. White
immediately chases the c5-bishop from its active position and puts pressure
on d4.} 13. Nb3 Be7 14. Re1 Rd8 15. Bd2 O-O 16. h4 $1 {A typical way to play
against the g6-knight. White provokes the weakening ...h7-h5.} h5 17. Rad1 a6
18. Nc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1d3,Gg2g4] A very strong maneuver. White's position is
strategically winning. White is planning to follow with Nd3 and g2-g4. Black
has no counterplay. 1-0 (33) Motylev,A (2677) -Maletin,P (2584)/Olginka 2011})
13. Nb3 O-O {The most logical continuation. Black finishes the development.} ({
After} 13... Nge7 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 15. b3 $14 {White enjoys a slight but lasting
advantage.}) (13... a5 $5 {This move is the best according to Stockfish. But
not always in structural positions of a closed type, the computer is right. Of
course, his recommendation deserves attention. Objectively, the positions are
complicated and playable.} 14. h4 (14. Bd2 a4 15. Nc1 $5 Bb4 16. Rd1 O-O 17.
Nd3 Bxd2 18. Rxd2 Rfd8 19. Rc1 $11) 14... a4 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16. Re1 h6 17. Bd2
O-O 18. Rac1 Nge7 19. h5 $132) ({After} 13... Rd8 {White plays in a typical
fashion -} 14. h4 h5 15. Bg5 Rd7 16. Nc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1d3]} O-O 17. a3 Be7 18.
Nd3 $14 {With an obvious advantage.}) 14. h4 $1 {Once again, we see this
thematic idea.} h5 $5 {Black keeps the stability of the knight but weakens the
kingside.} ({Another idea is} 14... h6 {when White can follow with} 15. h5 Nge7
16. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3,Gf2f4,Gg2g4,Gf4f5] Now, the f3-knight will be
relocated to d3. In this way, White prepares the advance of his kingside pawns.
} Nf5 (16... Bb4 $5 17. Nd3 Qa6 18. Bd2 ({At this point, White should have
played} 18. Nxb4 $1 {I managed to come up with the following forced sequence:}
Nxb4 19. Nxd4 Qxc4 20. b3 Qd5 21. Qg4 Qxe5 22. Bxh6 f5 23. Qxg7+ Qxg7 24. Bxg7
Kxg7 25. Nxe6+ Kf6 26. Nxf8 Rxf8 27. Rfd1 $14 {According to my analysis, White
should be slightly better in this endgame.}) 18... Qxc4 $15 {Gelfand-Karpov
2002 0.5-0.5 Cannes Master}) 17. g4 Nh4 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. f4 f5 (19... Qxc4 20.
Qh1 $1 $18) 20. exf6 Rxf6 21. b3 Qe7 22. Nd3 $16) 15. Bg5 {The bishop
immediately takes a strong position.} a5 16. Nc1 $1 {Strong maneuver. The
knight will be relocated to the blockade square d3, and at the same time it
will create threats to the king.} Rfc8 (16... Qxb2 17. Nd3 Qb6 18. Rab1 Qa7 19.
g4 $1 $40 hxg4 20. Qxg4 $18) 17. a3 {Prophylactic move. Keeping the knight
from an exchange.} Bf8 18. Nd3 $14 {White has the advantage. He has more space
and could potentially create an attack on the kingside.} *

