1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O h6 7. a4 $5 {This is
an interesting and relatively unexplored direction. The entire concept is very
rare in practical games. The main line 7.Nbd2 Nd7.8.Nb3 g5!? leads to unclear
and complicated positions in which there are many opportunities for both
colours. Playing 7.a4, White avoids this line. As we have seen on many
occasions, the main idea of White's last move is to gain space on the
queenside. In many cases, White closes the queenside and only then starts a
pawn expansion on the other wing.} c5 {Black immediately takes action. The
idea is to make use of the fact that 7.a4 weakens the queenside.} 8. Na3 $5 {
The knight is heading for the important b5-square. Another idea is to prepare
the c2-c4 break. White is better developed and should try to open the position.
} Nec6 ({After} 8... Nbc6 9. dxc5 Ng6 10. Be3 {Quite typically for this line,
White is trying to save the c5-pawn which gives space on the queenside and
restricts Black's pieces. Such a pawn is a valuable asset in many endgames.}
Ngxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. c4 $1 {Another thematic idea in this structure.
Black's centre falls apart.} dxc4 13. Nxc4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 $14 {
White enjoys a pleasant advantage in this endgame. The plan is simple: 1)
double the rooks along the d-file 2) start advancing the queenside pawns}) (
8... a6 {Too slow. White develops a dangerous initiative.} 9. dxc5 Nbc6 10. Be3
Ng6 {Black wastes too much time in order to win the e5-pawn. Meanwhile,
White can seize the opportunity to compromise Black's pawn structure by playing
} 11. Nd4 Ngxe5 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. c3 $14 {with a stable advantage.}) 9. c4 {
As mentioned earlier, this is an important breakthrough. White is ahead in
development and therefore any active actions are in his favour.} Be4 {According
to the computer, this is the best move in the position. It looks a bit strange
since Black makes another move with a developed piece. At the same time, the
remaining pieces are in their initial positions.} ({After} 9... Be7 10. cxd5
exd5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nb5 O-O 13. Bf4 $14 {White has more active pieces. Also,
the e5-pawn limits Black's actions.}) ({In a case of} 9... cxd4 {White gets
two bishops and a space advantage.} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nb5 Bc5 12. Nfxd4 Nxd4
13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O 15. Qf4 Qd7 16. b4 Nc6 17. Bb2 $14 {White enjoys a
stable advantage.}) ({Another possible direction is} 9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4
11. cxd5 exd5 ({The complications arising after} 11... Bxa3 12. Bb5+ Kf8 13.
Qxd4 $1 {favor White. Below, I provide some possible lines.} (13. Rxa3 Qxd5 $15
) 13... a6 (13... Be7 14. d6 Bg5 15. f4 Bh4 16. g3 $16) 14. Be2 Nc6 (14... Be7
15. d6 Bg5 16. f4 Bh4 17. g3 Nc6 18. Qf2 Bxg3 19. hxg3 $16) 15. Qd1 Qxd5 16.
Qxd5 exd5 17. Rxa3 Rd8 18. f4 $14 {White has a pair of bishops and a better pawn
structure. At the same time, Black struggles to coordinate his rooks.}) 12. Nb5
$16) ({The move} 9... Nd7 {does not solve the problems. At this point, I came
up with the following sequence:} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nb5 a6 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13.
exd6 c4 14. b3 $1 {White should play very dynamically. If Black manages to
complete the development he will be better.} c3 15. Bd3 Be4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17.
d5 Nb4 18. Qd4 O-O 19. Qxb4 exf3 20. Qxc3 fxg2 21. Re1 Rc8 22. Qd4 $16 {
with an obvious advantage.}) 10. Nb5 Nd7 {This is the most natural move. Black
just completes the development of his pieces.} 11. Be3 $5 {White puts
additional pressure in the centre. In the only game which features this
position, White followed with 11.Bf4 when the position is unclear.} (11. Bf4
Be7 12. Nc3 O-O $11 (12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Ndxe5 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. f3 Bh7 16.
cxd5 exd5 17. Nxd5 O-O 18. Bc7 Bc2 $1 19. Bxd8 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 Bxd1 21. Rfxd1
Rfxd8 $11 {Saric-Rodschtein 2016 0.5-0.5})) 11... cxd4 ({A very interesting
sequence arises after} 11... dxc4 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nd2 Bd5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15.
Nd6+ Kf8 16. f4 Nb3 {Black is forcing a transition in an endgame.} 17. Nxb3
Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Qxb3 19. Qc1 Nd4 20. Bxc4 Bxc4 21. Ra3 Qb4 22. Qxc4 Qxc4 23. Nxc4
Ke7 24. Nd6 $14 {Even in the endgame, Black has problems to solve. White has a
powerful knight on d6 and his next move would be Rc3, planning to invade the
c7-square.}) (11... Be7 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. exd6 b6 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. cxd5 Bxd5
16. Rc1 $14 {In this line, we can see how strong the e3-bishop can be.}) 12.
Nfxd4 dxc4 $1 {This is the correct reaction. Taking the e5-pawn can be
dangerous:} ({The worst option for Black is} 12... Ncxe5 $2 13. f3 Bh7 14. cxd5
exd5 15. Rc1 $16 {and the knight penetrates the c7-square.}) ({The better way
to take the pawn is} 12... Ndxe5 {Even in this case, however, Black remains
under pressure. The game may follow with} 13. f3 Bh7 14. cxd5 exd5 15. f4 Nxd4
16. Qxd4 Nc6 17. Qxd5 Be7 18. Rfd1 O-O 19. Qc4 Qc8 20. Rac1 $14 {White is
better developed while Black has very bad coordination.}) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 $5 {
This creative recapture allows Black to retain his extra pawn.} ({After} 13...
Bxc6 14. Nxa7 {White wins the pawn back with tempo and takes the initiative.}
Bd5 15. Nb5 Be7 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 O-O 18. Qe4 $14 {White is better.}) 14.
Nd6+ {The knight has reached its goal.} Bxd6 15. Qxd6 (15. exd6 Bd5 $11 {
Black has no problems.}) 15... Qb8 $1 {It is impossible to live with the
d6-queen for a long time.} 16. Qxb8+ Rxb8 17. Bxa7 Rxb2 18. Bxc4 Nxe5 19. Ba6
$5 {White keeps his bishop pair and continues to fight for an advantage.
Additionally, the powerful a4-pawn gives more than enough compensation.} (19.
Bxe6 {leads by force to an equal rook endgame.} fxe6 20. Bd4 Nd3 21. Bxb2 Nxb2
22. f3 Bg6 23. Rfb1 Bxb1 24. Rxb1 Kd7 25. Rxb2 Ra8 26. Ra2 $11) 19... f6 20. a5
Kf7 21. Rfd1 Ra8 22. Bd4 Rb3 23. Bf1 Nd3 24. Be3 $44 {With a full compensation.
} *

