Rb1 Ba5 {with a normal position.}) 11... Nd8 (11... Rb8 {deserves attention.
By exchanging the active rook, Black wants to reduce the pressure.
Nevertheless, with a precise play, White keeps the initiative.} 12. Rxb8+ Nxb8
13. Kd2 a6 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gh1b1,Gb1b7] As we are
going to witness on multiple occasions, the d6-pawn is very dangerous in this
line. While Black will be trying to complete the development, White will
manage to invade via the b-file. A possible line would be} Nf6 16. Rb1 Nbd7 17.
Kc1 $1 {Prophylactic against ...Ne4.} Ne4 18. Rb7 Nxd6 19. Ra7 Nb6 20. Rxa6
Nbc8 21. Bf4 Ne4 22. Ne5 f6 23. Ra8 Ke7 24. Nc6+ Kd7 25. Nb8+ Kd8 26. f3 Nc3
27. Bf1 $14 {White has an advantage. They have two bishops and a strong passed
pawn on the a-file.}) 12. Rc7 $1 (12. Rxa7 $2 {In this edition, the exchange
of rooks is in Black's favour!} Rxa7 13. Nxa7 Bxc2 14. O-O Ne7 15. Rc1 Bg6 $15 {
Black has a protected passed pawn which gives him an advantage.}) 12... Rb8 {
Activating the rook with the idea to penetrate the first rank.} ({After} 12...
Bxc2 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. exd6 Nf6 15. Re7+ Kf8 16. Ne5 h6 17. f3 $14 {White has
many advantages in this position - strong rook on e7, a dangerous pawn on d6,
