1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 Qb6 $5 7. Nc3 Nc6 {
This move marks the beginning of maybe the most principled way to fight the 3.
e5 system against the Caro-Kann. The arising positions are sharp and very
concrete knowledge is required. The good news is that from a practical
perspective Black's play is much more difficult. White has many safe ways to
force a draw.} ({French structures would arise after} 7... c4 $5 {Usually,
these positions are passive but reliable. It is not so easy to break Black's
pawn chain. Nevertheless, the passive waiting play is not everybody's cup of
tea.} 8. Rb1 {White must defend the pawn} Bb4 ({Similar is} 8... Nc6 9. Nh4 $1
{A key move in such position. Obtaining the bishop pair is an important part
of White's strategy. The play could continue} Bg6 10. O-O Qa5 11. a3 Be7 12.
Nxg6 hxg6 13. f4 Nh6 14. g4 $14 {White is better. The h6-knight is very
problematic.}) 9. Nh4 {The most principled continuation.} ({White can also
start with} 9. O-O {giving Black the chance to go wrong with} Nc6 $2 ({the
normal move is} 9... Ne7 {when after} 10. Nh4 {we transpose the main line.})
10. Bxc4 $1 {This is the point!} dxc4 11. d5 Qa6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. a3 Be7 14.
Nd4 $16) 9... Ne7 10. O-O Bxc3 {This seems to be the most reliable option. By
spoiling White's queenside structure, Black gets at least one static advantage
as a compensation for the lack of space.} ({After} 10... Nbc6 11. g4 {White
starts pushing his kingside pawns and develops the initiative.} Bg6 12. f4 h6
13. f5 Bh7 14. Na4 Qa6 15. b3 $1 {White opens a second battlefield. This idea
would not have been possible, had Black went for 10...Bxc3. Below, I provide a
possible line} b5 16. a3 $1 {White opens the queenside and dominated because
of his better development and bishop pair.} Bxa3 17. Ra1 Bb4 18. c3 bxa4 19.
cxb4 Nxb4 20. Rxa4 Qb6 21. Qd2 a5 22. bxc4 dxc4 23. d5 Qb5 24. dxe6 fxe6 25.
Ra3 $16) 11. bxc3 Qa6 12. Bg4 {This is the safe direction. White manages to
keep a stable pressure in all the lines.} ({Another option is} 12. Bg5 {
which leads to a sharp sequence. According to the computer, White has an
advantage, but the position is complicated and playing for both colours is not
easy.} Nbc6 13. Nxf5 Nxf5 14. g4 Nfe7 15. f4 h6 16. Bh4 h5 17. f5 hxg4 18. Bxe7
Nxe7 19. fxe6 f6 20. Bxg4 O-O-O 21. Qc1 Rh6 22. exf6 Qd6 23. Qd2 (23. Qf4 Qxf4
24. Rxf4 gxf6 $15) 23... Rxf6 24. Kg2 $14) 12... Bxg4 {With this exchange
Black is trying to slow down White's kingside play but allows the activation
of the queen.} ({After} 12... Bg6 {White can follow with} 13. f4 O-O 14. f5
exf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Rxf5 Nd7 18. Qf3 Qe6 19. h3 b6 20. Rb5 $16
{when the advantage is almost decisive.}) 13. Qxg4 Rg8 14. Qh5 h6 15. f4 {
[%cal Gf4f5]} g6 16. Qxh6 Nbc6 17. Qg5 Qxa2 18. Rfc1 O-O-O 19. Bd2 Nf5 20. Nf3
$14 {White is better thanks to the space advantage, weak dark squares in
Black's camp, and the kingside prospects.}) 8. O-O Qxb2 $1 {In this edition,
Black can take the pawn. Recently, top players have been discussing this
option. Many important games have been played on this subject. In this line,
the positions are very complicated and require deep analysis for both colours.}
({Bad is} 8... cxd4 $2 {due to} 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Qa5 11. Bb5+ $18) ({
Even here, Black can play} 8... c4 {going for the French structures.} 9. Nh4 $5
{White immediately goes for a dynamic play. It turns out that Black cannot
safely complete the development.} Bg6 ({In case of} 9... Qxb2 10. Nxd5 $1 {
White obtains a better endgame by force.} Bxc2 (10... exd5 11. Nxf5 $16) 11.
Qc1 Qxc1 12. Nc7+ Kd7 13. Rfxc1 Kxc7 14. Rxc2 Nge7 15. Bxc4 Rc8 16. Rb1 Kb8 17.
Bb5 $14 {White enjoys better development, space advantage, bishop pair.}) 10.
Bxc4 $5 {By temporarily sacrificing a piece, White opens up the position and
grabs the initiative. Black pieces are not developed and poorly coordinated.}
dxc4 11. d5 Qc7 12. dxc6 Qxc6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Qg4 Rh5 15. Bf4 Bb4 16. Ne2 Nh6
17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Nd4 Qd5 19. Nf3 $14 {White has an advantage.}) 9. Qe1 $1 {
This is the only way to fight for an advantage.} ({After the tempting} 9. Nb5
$6 c4 10. Nc7+ Kd7 11. Nxa8 Bxc2 12. Qc1 Ba3 $15 {Black has sufficient
compensation for the rook.}) 9... cxd4 {The most important line. White should
play very dynamically. If Black manages to successfully complete the
development, he will be simply better since there are no structural problems
in his position.} ({The move} 9... O-O-O $6 {is too risky. A possible line
would be} 10. Bb5 c4 11. a3 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga1a2]} Qxc2 12. Rb1 a6 13. Bxc6
bxc6 14. Ng5 $1 {Very strong move. White not only attacks the f7-pawn but also
prepares f2-f3 followed by Rf2.} Rd7 15. f3 h6 16. Rf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Bxb1 18.
Na4 $1 $18 {White is winning.}) (9... c4 $5 {An interesting opportunity. Black
sacrifices the queen for knight, rook, and two pawns. Very few games were
played in this position. Stockfish considers the position to be about equal,
but for a human, this position is complicated for both colours.} 10. Rb1 Qxc2 11.
Rxb7 ({The queen sacrifices can be seen in the line} 11. Bd1 Qxb1 $8 (11... Qd3
12. Ba4 $18) 12. Nxb1 Bxb1 13. Ba4 Bd3 14. Qa5 Kd7 15. Rd1 Nh6 $2 {This move
allows} ({Better would have been} 15... Nge7 $5 16. Rxd3 cxd3 17. Ng5 Nf5 $13 {
with an unclear position.}) 16. Bg5 $16 {Motylev-Donchenko 2017 1-0 Aeroflot
open.}) 11... Rb8 12. Rxb8+ Nxb8 13. Qa1 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf1c1]} Bb4 14.
Rb1 Bxc3 15. Rxb8+ Kd7 16. Qf1 $132 {The position remains unclear.
Nevertheless, practically speaking, it is easier to play with White.}) 10. Bxd4
