17. Na7 Rxc1 18. Qxc1 Be7 19. Nb6 Nxb6 20. Bxb6 O-O 21. Rd1 Qb7 22. Qc7 Qxc7
23. Bxc7 $16 {White enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 14. Nxc6 Qc7 15. Nd4 Be7 16.
Ndxb5 Qxe5 17. Bb6 O-O 18. a4 Nh4 19. Qd2 Qh5 20. f3 $16 {Black has no
compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Nc3 Qxe5 13. Ba4 {We have reached a critical
position in which Black faces some choice. He has an extra pawn but it is not
easy to complete the development.} Rc8 {This seems to be the most natural
reaction.} ({Worse is} 13... O-O-O {when after} 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qa4 $18 {
White is already winning.}) ({Black can also pin the knight with} 13... Rd8 {
White, however, has a powerful reaction at his disposal:} 14. Qb3 $1 b5 15.
Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Nxb5 $1 {This sacrifice is the point behind White's previous
play. The game might continue with} axb5 17. Bxb5 Be4 18. Qa4 Rc8 19. Rac1 Bd6
20. g3 O-O 21. Bxc6 Rxc6 22. Rxc6 Qf5 23. f3 Bxc6 24. Qxc6 Qd3 25. Bf2 $16 {
Black has no compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Rc1 ({Even more precise is} 14.
Re1 $18) 14... Nf5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Ne2 Nxe3 17. Rxc6 Ke7 18. fxe3 Qxe3+ 19.
Kh1 Rxc6 20. Bxc6 Qd3 21. Qa4 e5 22. Rd1 Qxe2 23. Qb4+ $18 {Volokitin-Fridman
2016 1-0}) ({The move} 9... Rc8 {is quite natural. This line tends to be more
positional.} 10. Nd2 a6 {Black should already get rid of the pin since White
is ready to follow with c2-c4.} ({The positional} 10... Bg6 {[%cal Ge7f5]
preparing ...Nf5 seems to be a bit slow. White can go for the following
sequence:} 11. c4 Nf5 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. Bxa7 Bd3 14. cxd5 Bxb5 15. dxc6 Rxc6
16. Re1 b6 {This attempt to trap the bishop doesn't work.} ({Black should
prefer} 16... Bb4 17. Be3 O-O 18. a3 Be7 19. Nf3 $14 {With a slight but stable
advantage for White.}) 17. Nb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3d4] The knight is heading for the
