development.} Qd7 {Strengthening move. Black is preparing the pawn advance
c6-c5. The alternatives are clearly worse.} ({The immediate} 11... dxc4 {
is well met by} 12. Qa4 {when a logical follow-up would be} Bd3 13. Rd1 Qd7 14.
Na3 c5 15. Ndb5 {Once again, Black should take care of the d6-square.} Nd5 16.
Nc7+ $1 Nxc7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. Nxc4 Nd5 19. Rxd3 Be7 20. Bd2 $14 {White
enjoys a better structure and a space advantage.}) ({Too slow is} 11... Bg6 12.
Nc3 {Now Black cannot complete the development because his knight is tied to
the defence of the c6-pawn. For example, with the knight being on c3, the move
12...Qd7 would run into 13.Na4!. Another typical idea can be seen in the line}
c5 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Ndb5 $18 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] and White is winning.}) ({
Rather premature is} 11... c5 {when Black will experience structural problems
after} 12. Nxf5 Nxf5 13. cxd5 Qxd5 ({After} 13... exd5 {Black cannot keep the
center intact. For example:} 14. Nc3 d4 15. Qf3 $1 Qc8 16. Nd5 Ra7 17. Bd2 $16
{White has a big advantage.}) 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Nc3 Be7 17. Na4 {
White is basically winning a pawn.} Rhb8 18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. Nxc5+ Ke7 20. b3 $14
{Black's compensation is far from obvious.}) 12. Nc3 {Connecting all the
pieces to the fight!} dxc4 {With this exchange, Black frees the outpost for
the knight on d5.} (12... c5 $2 13. Nxf5 Nxf5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qxd5 $18) (
12... Bg6 $2 13. Na4 Rb8 14. Rc1 $16) 13. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ga4c5,Ga4b6] A typical
idea in this structure. White makes use of the weakened dark-squares.} Nd5 14.
Nxf5 exf5 15. Rc1 c3 (15... Be7 16. Bc5 O-O 17. Rxc4 $14) 16. Qc2 $1 {There
are two ideas behind this powerful move. The first idea is to avoid the
