1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 Nd7 {This line has
always been very rare in practical games. In general, the combination Nd7 +
c6-c5 does not work very well since Black cannot put sufficient pressure on
the centre. Of course, Black's idea is to transfer his remaining knight to c6.
Nevertheless, this idea takes a lot of time.} 7. O-O Ne7 8. Nbd2 $5 {Finishing
the development of the pieces and preparing a breakthrough in the centre.
Black's main problem is that by playing the premature 5...c5 he started the
fight in the centre with unfinished development.} cxd4 {Black releases the
tension and prepares to take the e5-pawn.} ({The move} 8... Nc6 $6 {is dubious
since White immediately opens the centre and begins active actions.} 9. c4 cxd4
10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Be4 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $16 {White's
advantage is almost decisive.}) 9. Nxd4 Nxe5 {Black accepts the challenge and
takes the dangerous pawn. This leads to serious difficulties for him.} (9...
Nc6 {This passive move allows White to spoil the opponent's structure. A
logical sequence would be} 10. Nxf5 exf5 11. Nf3 Bc5 12. Bg5 $1 Be7 13. Bxe7
Nxe7 14. c4 Nb6 15. cxd5 Qxd5 16. a4 $16) 10. c4 $1 {White breaks in the
centre and prepares to bring the queen into the attack.} N5c6 11. Qa4 {Now,
the pressure on the c6-knight is tremendous. It is already impossible for
Black to finish the development.} ({Another way to develop the initiative
would be} 11. N2b3 $5 Rc8 12. Rc1 Bg6 13. Nc5 b6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qa4 $18 {
with a winning position.}) 11... Qd7 ({Maybe a better practical chance would
have been} 11... Qa5 12. Qxa5 Nxa5 13. Nb5 Rd8 14. Bxa7 $14 {with difficult
but still playable position for Black.}) 12. Nxf5 Nxf5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bg4 {
The pin along the h3-c8 diagonal is very annoying.} h5 15. Bh3 Be7 16. Nf3 g6
17. Rae1 O-O (17... Rd8 18. Bg5 Kf8 19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. Bxe7+ Nxe7 21. Qxa7 $16)
18. Nd4 $16 {White controls the entire board. His advantage is out of question.
} *

