1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 {Recently, this line became very fashionable. Black
is going for a French type of position. Compared to 3...Bf5, this system
requires less theoretical knowledge from Black. At the same time, the entire
concept is quite reasonable. It is not easy to demonstrate a clear-cut way to
the advantage for White.} 4. dxc5 {This is the most principled approach. Now,
Black will spend time on winning the c5-pawn back.} e6 {This is the most
popular move among top-players. Black is trying to immediately regain the pawn.
} (4... Nc6 {is dealt with in the next chapter.}) 5. Be3 {This rare move
appears to be quite challenging. Black should play very accurately in order
not to find himself in a difficult position.} (5. a3 $5 {is the main line.})
5... Nd7 $1 {This is the most accurate move order. Black is immediately
attacking the c5-pawn.} ({A typical reaction is} 5... Ne7 {with the idea to
bother White's e3-bishop by means of Nf5. According to Stockfish, this
continuation does not give Black an equal position.} 6. Nf3 Nf5 ({The attempt
to win the e5-pawn with} 6... Nbc6 7. Bd3 $5 Ng6 {is rather time-consuming. I
think that White should play} (7... Qa5+ 8. Nbd2 Ng6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. O-O $16)
8. Bxg6 hxg6 9. Nc3 Rh5 10. h4 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Rxe5 12. Qd4 Rh5 13. O-O-O $36 {
with a very dangerous initiative.}) 7. Bg5 Qc7 8. Bd3 {White has more space
and better-developed pieces.} h6 (8... Bxc5 9. Nc3 {This is an important move.
White creates 2 threats - 10.Bxf5 and 10.Nb5.} Ne7 10. Nb5 Qb6 11. O-O {[%csl
Rc5][%cal Gb2b4] Now, Black should take care of his restricted c5-bishop.
White is already planning to play b2-b4.} a6 12. Nbd4 {White is better. Black
is dommed to passivity. Taking the pawn with} Qxb2 {does not solve the
problems. After} 13. Nb3 Ba7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Rb2,Re7] Black
has problems with his vulnerable king and restricted queen.}) 9. Bc1 Bxc5 {
It is important for Black to get rid of the c5-pawn.} ({Going after the
central pawn with} 9... Nc6 {is not advisable. A possible line would be} 10.
O-O Nxe5 11. Bxf5 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 exf5 13. b4 Be7 14. Bb2 a5 15. a3 $16 {
White enjoys a better pawn structure and kingside pressure.}) 10. Nc3 {[%cal
Gd3f5]} Ne7 11. Nb5 Qb6 12. O-O {[%cal Gb2b4] Once again, Black should decide
how to deal with his problematic c5-bishop. A typical sequence would be} Bd7
13. a4 a6 14. a5 Qc6 15. Nfd4 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Qc7 17. Re1 Nbc6 18. Nxc6 Nxc6 19.
Qg4 $16 {with complete domination.}) ({Another way to develop the king's
knight is} 5... Nh6 {In this line, however, Black usually accepts an inferior
pawn structure.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 (6... Nf5 7. Bg5 {transposes to 5...Ne7.}) 7. Bxh6
gxh6 8. Bb5 Bxc5 {This position arose in the game 1/2 (28) Najer, E (2647)
-Khenkin, I (2650) Czechia 2012. At this point, my suggestion is} 9. O-O $5 Bd7
10. Qe2 a6 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. c3 Rg8 {Black is trying to create
threats on the kingside. White, however, can restrict Black's bishops by
making use of the important d4-square. My analysis goes} 14. b4 Be7 15. a4 Rc8
16. Nd4 Bd7 17. a5 Qa7 18. g3 $14 {White is better. He has a better structure
and more space. In this closed position, the knights are definitely superior
to the bishops.}) ({Premature is} 5... Nc6 6. f4 d4 7. Bf2 Bxc5 8. Nd2 $14 {
[%cal Gg1f3,Gf1d3,Gd2e4] Black's d4-pawn should be considered as a weakness.
White's play is quite simple. He would just make normal moves such as Nf3, Bd3,
0-0, and Ne4.}) ({Dubious is} 5... Qc7 {The early development of the queen
contradicts classical chess education. As you can notice, all the other
black pieces remain on their initial positions.} 6. Nc3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc3b5]
White is immediately taking advantage of the position of Black's queen. The
knight is going to b5.} Bd7 ({The alternative} 6... a6 {allows} 7. Na4 {
Of course, White will be trying to keep the c5-pawn as long as possible.} Nd7
8. Bd3 Nxc5 (8... Nxe5 {runs into} 9. b4 $16 {As usual, the c5-pawn restricts
Black's pieces.}) 9. Nxc5 Bxc5 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 11. Qg4 {A key idea. Had the
black knight already been on e7, Black would have just castled. Now, however,
he is forced to weaken the kingside with} g6 {The play would continue} 12. Nf3
Ne7 13. O-O O-O 14. h4 $16 {[%csl Rc8] White has more space and good attacking
chances. As usual in the French structures, the c8-bishop is rather passive.})
7. Nb5 Bxb5 8. Bxb5+ Nc6 9. b4 $14 {White is better due to his bishop pair and
extra space. 1-0 (24) Ponkratov,P (2630)-Piorun,K (2634) St Petersburg 2018})
6. Nf3 Bxc5 {The most logical move. Black wins the pawn back and develops the
bishop.} ({Delaying the capture of the pawn with} 6... Ne7 {gives White the
possibility to carry out the thematic} 7. c4 $1 {challenging Black's centre.}
dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nf5 9. Bf4 Bxc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 Nb6 12. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,
Ga1d1,Gc3e4] In the middlegame, the e5-pawn is very strong. White's extra
space and mobile pieces give him the opportunity to gradually prepare his
kingside play. In the future, he can follow with simple moves like Qe2, Rad1,
and Ne4.}) ({The move} 6... Nxc5 $6 {is best answered with} 7. c4 $1 {Again,
we see this typical idea. Forcing play does not help Black either. For example:
} Ne4 8. cxd5 Qa5+ 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Qxd5 11. Rc1 Bd7 12. Bc4 Qe4+ 13. Be2
Bb5 14. Be3 Qb4+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Bxd2 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 $16 {White's better
development gives him a huge advantage in the endgame.}) 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 8. Qd4 {
White gains an important tempo. The main idea is to transfer the queen to the
kingside. Of course, the g4-square would be the perfect spot!} Qb6 $1 {The
most precise move. Black defends the knight and attacks the b2-pawn, thus not
giving White time to play Qg4. The alternatives are worse:} ({After} 8... b6 9.
Qg4 $1 Kf8 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. O-O-O Bd7 12. Kb1 Qc7 13. Bd3 $14 {White is better
due to his extra space and better coordination.}) ({Nothing changes} 8... Qc7
9. Qg4 {creating new weakness on the kingside.} f5 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Bb5+ Kf7
12. Qd4 Rf8 13. O-O b6 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Ne5+ Kg8 16. Rad1 $14 {White dominates
the dark squares.}) 9. Nbd2 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Gd2b3,Ga2b3] The knight goes to
b3. After the eventual exchange of the knights, White will have the a-file
open for his rook.} Ne7 $1 {The most accurate move. The idea is that after
exchanging the queens, Black manages to put his knight on g6, attacking the
e5-pawn. In this case, White does not have time to protect the pawn by means
of f2-f4.} ({Less precise is} 9... Bd7 {when White gets a stable advantage in
the endgame thanks to the strong d4-knight.} 10. Nb3 Rc8 ({Opening the a-file
with} 10... Nxb3 11. axb3 {is in White's favour.} Qxd4 12. Nxd4 {[%csl Ra7]
[%cal Gb3b4,Ge1d2,Gf1d3,Gf2f4,Gb4b5,Ga1a3,Gh1a1] We have a classical French
endgame which is terrible for Black. White can start playing on both wings
since Black is completely deprived of counterplay. A possible set-up would be
Bd3, f2-f4, b4-b5, and Kd2. Later on, White can double his rooks along the
a-file.} f6 ({Exchanging the d4-knight with} 12... Ne7 13. f4 Nc6 {does not
help. There are is a tremendous difference in the activity of the bishops.} 14.
Nxc6 Bxc6 15. b4 Ke7 16. b5 {[%csl Ra7]} Bd7 17. Bd3 Rhb8 18. b3 $16 {[%cal
Ge1d2,Gd2e3,Ge3d4,Ga1a3,Gh1a1] White is strategically winning. In the future,
he can transfer his king all the way to d4 and then double the rooks on the
a-file.}) 13. f4 fxe5 14. fxe5 Nh6 15. Bd3 Nf7 16. Nf3 Ke7 ({The position
arising after} 16... g5 17. h4 g4 18. Ng5 Nxe5 19. Bxh7 Ke7 20. Kf2 Nf7 21. Kg3
$16 {is favourable for White. His kingside passed pawn is very strong.}) 17. h4
a6 18. h5 Bb5 19. Bxb5 axb5 20. Kd2 $14 {White is clearly better.}) 11. Nxc5
Qxc5 12. Qxc5 Rxc5 13. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1d2,Gf3d4,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] Of course, White
enjoys a pleasant advantage in this endgame. The set-up is quite standard -
the king goes to d2 while the knight occupies the d4-square. Afterwards, White
starts gaining space on the kingside by means of f2-f4-f5. Black's position is
very passive.} Nh6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh6f7] Black is planning to put pressure on e5
by means of ...f7-f6 followed by ...Nf7.} ({The alternative is} 13... Ne7 14.
Kd2 O-O 15. Rae1 $1 {An important nuance. The other rook will occupy the
f1-square in order to support the advance of the f-pawn.} f6 16. Rhf1 Bb5 17.
Nd4 Bd7 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. g4 Rf4 20. Nxe6 Bxe6 21. Rxe6 $16 {White had a huge
advantage in 1-0 (42) Paravyan,D (2423)-Gavrilov,A (2466) Moscow 2014}) 14. Kd2
f6 15. Rae1 Ke7 16. Rhf1 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gf2f4]} Nf7 {preventing Nd4.} 17. c3 g5
18. Re3 {White is ready to double the rooks and take the e5-square under
control.} h6 (18... fxe5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 h6 21. f4 Rf8 ({Maybe Black
could fight for equality after} 21... Kd6 22. Re3 Rcc8 23. a3 Rcf8 24. Ref3 Bc6
25. fxg5 Rxf3 26. Rxf3 hxg5 27. h3 Ke7 $11 {In any case, White's play remains
simpler.}) 22. fxg5 $16) 19. exf6+ Kxf6 20. Rfe1 Re8 21. Ne5 Nxe5 22. Rxe5 b6
23. g3 Rg8 24. a3 Rcc8 25. f3 $14 {Black's counterplay is restricted. White
enjoys small but stable advantage.}) 10. Nb3 Nxb3 {The most reliable
continuation. Black goes into an equal endgame. In which success depends on
the skill of playing the endgame.} ({White keeps an edge after} 10... Ne4 11.
Qxb6 axb6 12. a3 Bd7 13. Nbd4 O-O 14. Bd3 Nc5 15. O-O Nxd3 16. cxd3 $14) ({and
} 10... Nd7 11. Qxb6 Nxb6 12. Bd3 Bd7 13. O-O-O h6 14. Kb1 $14) 11. axb3 Qxd4
12. Nxd4 Ng6 $1 {Black does not give his opponent the opportunity to play the
important move f2-f4. White is forced to retreat with his knight.} ({After} 
12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ra5 Ke7 15. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Ge1d2,Gh1a1] White has
a big advantage.}) 13. Nf3 {The only way to protect the pawn.} f6 $1 {Black
challenges White's centre and prepares to bring his c8-bishop into play.} 14.
exf6 gxf6 15. g3 $5 {Developing the bishop on the diagonal h1-a8, White tries
to create pressure on the d5-pawn. I consider this move to be White's best
practical chance.} e5 16. Bg2 Be6 17. O-O {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3,Gf2f4]
Objectively speaking, Black should be able to hold this endgame. Nevertheless,
I think that White's play is simpler. At least he has a clear plan at his
disposal - Ne1-d3 followed by f2-f4, thus weakening Black's centre.} a6 18. Ne1
{[%cal Ge1d3] The knight is heading for d3, where it will be multifunctional.}
Kf7 19. Nd3 Rhc8 20. f4 $5 {This is the most energetic continuation. White
sacrifices a pawn but obtains sufficient compensation.} (20. c3 Ne7 21. b4 b6
$11 {equal endgame arises.}) 20... exf4 (20... e4 21. f5 exd3 22. fxe6+ Ke7 23.
cxd3 $16) 21. Rf2 fxg3 22. hxg3 Kg7 23. Raf1 Bg8 (23... Rf8 24. Nc5 Rae8 25.
Nxb7 $14) 24. c3 Rc6 25. Nb4 (25. b4 Re8 26. Nc5 $44) 25... Rd6 26. Nc2 $44 *

