1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 Nc6 {This move is less critical than 4...e6.
Since the c5-pawn is not attacked, White gets a valuable time to decide how to
strengthen the centre. In this position, I decided to recommend the rare} 5. f4
$5 {Strengthening the central pawn and preparing the comfortable development
of the pieces.} e6 {The most logical. Black immediately wants to win the pawn
back. Other options for Black look dubiously.} ({Bringing the bishop outside
the pawn chain with} 5... Bf5 {would cost Black another important tempo. A
possible line would be} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Be3 {It is already impossible to win the
c5-pawn back.} Bg4 8. c3 Nh6 9. Nbd2 Nf5 10. Bf2 Be7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Nxf3 $16 {
White has a healthy extra pawn.}) ({Another way to bring the bishop out is} 
5... Nh6 6. Nf3 Bg4 {This approach fails to solve the opening problems.} ({
In the game 1-0 (43) Fedoseev,V (2724)-Perez Ponsa,F (2553) chess.com INT 2018,
Black played} 6... Bf5 $6 {In this line, Black cannot win the pawn back. White
could have played} 7. Be3 $5 e6 8. Bb5 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Qa5 11. Nc3 Rfd8 {
Now, White can transform his material advantage into a positional one.} 12.
Bxc6 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 14. Nd4 bxc6 15. Qd2 Be4 16. g4 $16 {Black is
strategically lost.}) 7. Bd3 e6 8. Be3 d4 {In this way, Black regains the pawn
but gives White the important e4-square which is a perfect base for White's
kingside activity.} ({After} 8... Nf5 9. Bxf5 Bxf5 10. c3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12.
Nbd2 $14 {Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Bf2 Bxc5
10. h3 Bf5 11. g4 {[%csl Rh6] Important idea. White gains space and restricts
the h6-knight.} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Rc8 13. a3 Qb6 14. Nbd2 $1 {Of course! The
knight is going to e4 without taking the b2-pawn into account. After} Qxb2 15.
O-O Qc3 16. Ne4 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Be7 18. Nxd4 $14 {White is better since he has
more space and the h6-knight is out of play.}) 6. Be3 {The idea of this move
is to provoke the advance ...d5-d4. Otherwise, the bishop will occupy the
powerful diagonal a7-g1.} d4 7. Bf2 Bxc5 ({The game 1-0 (36) Moussard, J (2591)
-Arkell,K (2453) London 2018 saw} 7... g5 $2 {which is too optimistic. Black
pieces are not ready for action. My suggestion would be} 8. Nd2 $1 gxf4 9. Qh5
Qd5 10. Ngf3 Nf6 11. Qh4 Nd7 12. Qxf4 Ndxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 14. Qxe5 Nxe5 15.
Bxd4 $16) 8. Nd2 Nge7 {This is the most natural square for the knight.} ({
Dubious is} 8... Nh6 {since in most cases, the knight on the edge of the board
is poor.} 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Ngf3 Nb4 {Black wants to eliminate the d3-bishop but
weakens the d4-pawn.} 11. Nb3 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Bb4+ 13. Nbd2 b6 14. O-O-O Bb7 15.
Rhg1 f6 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. g3 Rac8 18. Bxd4 Qf5 19. Qxf5 Nxf5 20. Bf2 $16 {
Black does not have compensation for the missing pawn.}) ({Attacking the
b2-pawn with} 8... Qb6 {is not dangerous. As usual, White keeps developing his
pieces and doesn't pay attention to the pawn.} 9. Bd3 Nge7 ({Accepting the
sacrifice is dangerous:} 9... Qxb2 10. Ngf3 Nge7 11. O-O Nd5 12. Rb1 Qa3 13.
Nc4 Nc3 14. Nxa3 Nxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxa3 16. Nxd4 $16 {The material is equal but
White's advantage in the development is enormous.}) 10. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a5
11. Ne2 O-O 12. O-O Nd5 13. Ne4 Ne3 14. Bxe3 dxe3 15. Rf3 Rd8 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17.
Qe1 $16 {It turns out that the e3-pawn will be lost. Black has no counterplay.}
) 9. Bd3 $5 {This is the exact move order. White is planning to develop his
knight via the e2-square.} Nd5 10. Ne2 $5 {As mentioned earlier, on e2 the
knight is very flexible. It defends the f4-pawn and can participate in
different attacking ideas.} O-O ({Dubious is} 10... Ne3 $6 {when White should
play} 11. Bxe3 dxe3 12. Ne4 Be7 (12... Bb6 13. Nd6+ $16) 13. N2c3 {[%cal Gd1f3,
Ge1c1] White is already preparing his kingside attack. At the same time, it
becomes clear that the e3-pawn will be lost.} O-O 14. Qf3 Qb6 15. O-O-O h6 16.
Rhe1 $16) 11. O-O Ne3 {The most principled approach. Black hopes that his
e3-pawn and bishop pair will compensate White's better pawn structure.} ({
Worse is} 11... b6 12. a3 a5 13. Ne4 Nce7 14. Qd2 Nf5 15. Nxc5 bxc5 {At this
point, White can demonstrate the drawbacks of Black's position by means of} 16.
Bxf5 exf5 17. c3 {It becomes clear that Black's position is overextended.} Ba6
18. cxd4 cxd4 19. Bxd4 $16) 12. Bxe3 dxe3 13. Ne4 Bb6 {The best position for
the bishop.} ({A way too passive is} 13... Be7 {White should start with} 14. c3
{[%csl Gd4] taking the d4-square under control and preparing N2g3 followed by
Qe2.} b5 15. N2g3 b4 16. Qe2 Qb6 {At this point, White can just win the
e3-pawn by playing 17.Rae1. At the same time, he has good attacking prospects
which are well illustrated by the following sequence:} 17. Qh5 $1 e2+ 18. Rf2
h6 19. Nf6+ Kh8 20. Ng4 $16 {[%cal Gg4h6]} Ba6 21. Bxa6 Qxa6 22. Nxh6 g6 23.
Qxe2 Qxe2 24. Rxe2 $16) ({Another option is} 13... Qb6 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 15. c3 {
[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3e4] After parting with the dark-squared bishop, Black has no
counterplay. The e3-pawn will be gradually besieged.} b5 16. Qc2 h6 17. Ng3 Ne7
18. Ne4 Qb6 19. Qe2 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) 14. c4 $5 {A reliable
continuation. White wants to block the a7-g1 diagonal, and gradually win the
e3-pawn.} ({Interesting is} 14. Qe1 $5 {with the idea to transfer the queen to
the kingside and start attacking.}) 14... Nb4 (14... f5 15. exf6 gxf6 16. c5
Bc7 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. cxd6 Kh8 19. Be4 e5 20. Qd3 exf4 21. Rxf4 $16) 15. Bb1
Qxd1 {Black tries to save the game with exchanges. The endgame, however, is
not easy.} 16. Rxd1 a5 ({Probably, more reliable would have been} 16... Nc6 {
I managed to find the following sequence which is not entirely forced but
illustrates the character of the position.} 17. c5 Bd8 18. Bd3 b6 19. Nd6 bxc5
20. Be4 Bd7 21. b4 Rb8 (21... cxb4 22. Rac1 $18) 22. bxc5 f6 23. Nc4 Be8 24.
Rd6 Rc8 25. Rc1 Be7 26. Rxe6 Bd7 27. Rd6 Bxd6 28. Nxd6 fxe5 29. Nxc8 Rxc8 30.
fxe5 Nxe5 31. Rc3 $14 {White keeps his advantage.}) 17. a3 Nc6 18. c5 Bd8 19.
Bd3 {White has a stable advantage. Gradually, he will win the e3-pawn when the
position would be technically winning.} b6 20. b4 axb4 21. Bb5 Ne7 22. axb4
Rxa1 23. Rxa1 $16 *

